I have for sell is a 1918 L.C smith specialty trap 12 gauge this is a trap shotgun the barrel is Hi nitro steel 32" it's the original bluing I would rate it at 80%  the wood furniture has no cracks real nice grain in stock butt pad has dog the receiver is great shape also has dog and a pair of pheasants with scroll work has ivory and brass bead sights locks up tight fires just fine with out problems injects spent round just fine email me for more photos and make me a offer I'm open for firearm trades I can ship with being you pay for shipping fees please no low ball offers I won't respond these are very find firearms.

Some information on the LC smith collectors association site 
More SBT guns (1,470) were built in Specialty Grade than any other; one gun in this grade was finished by the L.C. Smith Gun Company in 1948 after Hunter Arms production stopped at 1,469 in 1940. The Specialty was a mid-grade gun selling for $133 in 1927 allowing many options from which to choose: different stock dimensions of full, half or straight grip and 30, 32 and 34 inch barrels of Nitro Steel. Standard features include two Lyman ivory sights, ejector, ventilated rib, beavertail forearm and recoil pad. Engraving patterns usually consist of a sitting dog on the left of the frame and a sitting bird on the right, both surrounded by foliage and moderate scroll. Some early guns such as shown here have a standing dog on each side.   Most Specialtys have a silver inlay at the junction of the ventilated and solid portion of the rib near the breech end but specimens have been noted with gold and no inlays. The rib inlays only appear on Specialty’s and higher grades and are mostly found in gold on the higher grades. Barrels are usually roll stamped “L.C. SMITH SPECIALTY TRAP” on the left side.

title: For Sale:  Very Rare First-Generation Whaling Harpoon Gun
postcontent:
This is a very Rare First - Generation Swivel Whaling Harpoon Gun made By Wallis of Hull.

It is an original Flintlock converted to Dual Percussion Hammers!

It is 44 inches long x 7 3/8 inches wide - Circa 1800.

A rare and impressive whaling gun from the earliest period of firearm innovation in the fishing industry, this English Whaling Harpoon Gun is a stout and serious instrument that revolutionized whaling. Made by George Wallis of Hull, he is recognized as the first successful maker of the swivel-mounted harpoon gun, circa 1800. The author William Scoresby indicates this period to have been 1772-1792, while other later sources credit the invention to 1800-1815.

When originally made, this Wallis gun had two flintlock hammers that worked off a single trigger, and have long ago been converted to two dual-percussion cap hammers, that would have lanyard triggers threaded out the locks to be fired simultaneously, ensuring the firing of the harpoon. With a full charge, it had an accurate range up to 40 yards. The name Wallis of Hull is on the iron barrel, amongst the heavy aged pitting, deep rust and signs of use under an old remnant of black oil paint. The left brass hammer compartment is marked “SHIP”.

Owning a deadly presence, the gun barrel is a stout 30½ inches in length with a 2½ inch diameter with a 1¾ inch bore, while the overall harpoon gun is 43¼ inches, plus the split-shaft barbed harpoon with ring for line attachment. The English Society of the Arts had paid premiums to whale men and artisans in the 1790s and early 1800s for those showing innovation and improvement in the use of the guns and harpoons. When William Greener substantially changed the design and powder of this type of harpoon gun in 1837, the new styles became known as Greener guns. This older gun was kept in use during this period, as indicated by its conversion.

title: For Sale:  1930s Crecent Arms 16 gauge Victor Ejector
postcontent:
I have for sale an old Crescent Arms 16 gauge Victor Ejector single barrel shotgun,from the 1930s. 

Crescent was a major arms producer for hardware stores, sporting goods retailers, and five and dimes across the country between 1892 to about 1930 when it was sold to a subsidiary of the Savage Arms Company which continued to make shotguns with the Crescent name until 1940. All Crescent records were lost or destroyed during a scrap paper drive in 1943 so my best estimate in this was from the later years, before the buyout. There have literally been books that include the history of Crescent Arms.

This particular shotgun was found in my basement ceiling after having lived here for over a decade. It is at least 80 years old and shows its age well. It had some pitting and had rust when found, which I carefully removed without disturbing the patina. I am not a gunsmith and cannot say with certainty that it is safe to fire but it seems to be functional. I also has a Lyman choke on it.

The history and story behind this is more fun to me than actually owning it. If you have any more info on this let me know or if you would like to own the shotgun and choke I'm asking $65 obo.

title: For Sale:  Colt King Cobra 357 4"
postcontent:
I have a very nice Colt King Cobra 4" 357 Magnum Stainless Steel revolver for sale.  I got some info from a collector (thanks!) who pointed out that it is the "Enhanced" version (larger Anaconda cylinder release, a moved over colt stamp, etc) from 1995 model AA3040E.  It is in great condition, very clean and perfect mechanically. 

Interestingly it has a unique vent rib barrel rather than a solid rib, similar to the Python.  The muzzle end of the barrel is also countersunk, this may be a gunsmith job or custom from Colt.  Real collectors would love to get their hands on a custom Colt from the factory, but there is perhaps a chance that this could be aftermarket.  The only way to know all the details about this specific gun is to have it "lettered" by Colt, which takes 100 days and $75.  I have a blue plastic Colt box that it fits in (might be original to the gun), the correct original black colt rubber grips (the slot in grip screw is a bit torqued by some dummy), a set of nice goncalo alves fancy wood grips. 

I'm going to value the revolver at maybe $1500.00 and see what kind of response I get.  I've been offered $1200.  If I can't get a bit closer to asking price, I am going to send for the Colt letter from the factory, so it will be off the market for a while.  I am open to trade ideas and partial trades.  Maybe you have 2 or 3 lesser guns for trade?  I'd take gold or silver at spot price, or plain cash money would work.  Send me an offer by email, I will respond. Private owner, CCW here, will only sell to legal buyer, Florida resident, over 21, no felons.

Product Information:
This is a factory original, drop-free magazine for your Glock. Glock magazines have a hardened steel insert encased in high tech polymer. This polymer coating protects the magazine and prevents deformation, even when dropped from a great height. 

Technical Information:
Glock magazines have very stiff springs when new and may be extremely difficult to load to full capacity. It may be necessary to use a Glock magazine loader (generally included in the Glock case with the handgun) to load the magazine to capacity or near capacity. 

If the last round appears impossible to load, for example if the magazine should hold 15 rounds and it will only accept 14, leave it loaded with 14 rounds for several days to allow the spring's tension to decrease. After a short time, the magazine should then accept its full capacity, but it may still be necessary to use the magazine loader.
